WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.460 --> 00:00:05.615
Prof: Okay,
today's discussion relies on

00:00:05.615 --> 00:00:08.847
three books,
and one of them is Hayek's

00:00:08.847 --> 00:00:14.830
Constitution of Liberty,
which you've seen two chapters

00:00:14.830 --> 00:00:16.149
of online.
 

00:00:16.149 --> 00:00:21.809
Another is Hernando de Soto's
Mystery of Capital and

00:00:21.809 --> 00:00:25.614
the third, and by far most
entertaining,

00:00:25.614 --> 00:00:30.200
is Aravind Adiga's,
The White Tiger.

00:00:30.200 --> 00:00:35.396
In today's class we're talking
about something really

00:00:35.396 --> 00:00:39.792
foundational,
and it is basically a pragmatic

00:00:39.792 --> 00:00:43.290
or practical theory of freedom.
 

00:00:43.290 --> 00:00:45.800
It's: Why is freedom a good
thing?

00:00:45.800 --> 00:00:53.740
This is a much less high-flown
theory than many philosophers

00:00:53.740 --> 00:00:55.490
would give.
 

00:00:55.490 --> 00:00:58.580
Hayek after all was an
economist.

00:00:58.580 --> 00:01:03.112
But it is a powerful one,
and for me it corresponds more

00:01:03.112 --> 00:01:05.420
or less to my convictions.
 

00:01:05.420 --> 00:01:12.992
The most powerful aspect of it
is that I can profit from your

00:01:12.992 --> 00:01:18.420
freedom, and you can profit from
my mine.

00:01:18.420 --> 00:01:24.470
Freedom is a common good.
 

00:01:24.470 --> 00:01:30.408
Individual freedom is a common
good in a way that makes a great

00:01:30.408 --> 00:01:35.101
deal of practical common sense
to a lot of people,

00:01:35.101 --> 00:01:36.730
including me.
 

00:01:36.730 --> 00:01:43.052
We'll do it in four chunks;
we'll begin by looking at

00:01:43.052 --> 00:01:45.319
Hayek's framework.
 

00:01:45.319 --> 00:01:52.235
We will then take up briefly
the question of government and

00:01:52.235 --> 00:01:56.170
how government relates to this.
 

00:01:56.170 --> 00:02:02.444
Then we will look at de Soto's
analysis of live and dead

00:02:02.444 --> 00:02:09.516
capital and his explanation of
why undeveloped countries remain

00:02:09.516 --> 00:02:12.938
undeveloped in many cases.
 

00:02:12.938 --> 00:02:19.062
Then finally we'll rub our idea
of freedom up against the lives

00:02:19.062 --> 00:02:24.098
of the central players in The
White Tiger.

00:02:24.098 --> 00:02:34.702
Throughout this I'm going to
advert from time to time to a

00:02:34.702 --> 00:02:37.120
Yale story.
 

00:02:37.120 --> 00:02:42.335
Not the tragic one that is on
the front page of today's paper

00:02:42.335 --> 00:02:45.524
but an equally--
well no I won't say equally--

00:02:45.524 --> 00:02:49.503
another troubling story,
which is the decision of Yale

00:02:49.503 --> 00:02:54.553
University Press when it agreed
to publish a book about the

00:02:54.553 --> 00:02:59.690
Danish cartoons which poked fun
at the prophet Mohammed.

00:02:59.690 --> 00:03:06.008
When that book was ready for
printing three months ago the

00:03:06.008 --> 00:03:11.218
director of Yale University
Press called me,

00:03:11.218 --> 00:03:13.979
I'm on his--I'm on the
committee that decides what

00:03:13.979 --> 00:03:16.818
books they publish--
and the question was:

00:03:16.818 --> 00:03:20.020
Can we pull the cartoons out of
the book?

00:03:20.020 --> 00:03:26.960
These are cartoons which make
devout Muslims very mad.

00:03:26.960 --> 00:03:35.264
And the answer we arrived at,
very reluctantly,

00:03:35.264 --> 00:03:40.500
was: Yes pull the cartoons.
 

00:03:40.500 --> 00:03:46.583
And that--think of that
problem, and think of what

00:03:46.583 --> 00:03:54.405
possible explanation could there
be why a great university feels

00:03:54.405 --> 00:04:01.854
itself unwilling to stand up for
freedom of expression in the

00:04:01.854 --> 00:04:08.310
case of these admittedly
blasphemous cartoons.

00:04:08.310 --> 00:04:12.908
It turns out the answer is very
practical and I'll give you my

00:04:12.908 --> 00:04:15.699
position on it by the end of
class.

00:04:15.699 --> 00:04:27.040
Okay, Hayek was a charming guy
and a very practical thinker;

00:04:27.040 --> 00:04:33.105
less practical perhaps then
economists who work for banks,

00:04:33.105 --> 00:04:37.790
but as Nobel laureates go,
very practical.

00:04:37.790 --> 00:04:43.639
He was given to thinking about
hard cases;

00:04:43.639 --> 00:04:47.740
about why things were done as
they were.

00:04:47.740 --> 00:04:53.069
And he was most of all an
intellectual skeptic.

00:04:53.069 --> 00:04:59.180
He was most of all inclined to
doubt human knowledge,

00:04:59.180 --> 00:05:05.699
to lean on fallibility and
ignorance,

00:05:05.699 --> 00:05:12.939
to look at Marxist historicism,
which we discussed last time,

00:05:12.939 --> 00:05:15.240
as horse feathers.
 

00:05:15.240 --> 00:05:22.240
He was contemptuous of not Marx
alone,

00:05:22.240 --> 00:05:28.004
but of whomsoever imagines that
there is a deterministic course

00:05:28.004 --> 00:05:33.620
for world history (a),
and that they know what is (b);

00:05:33.620 --> 00:05:37.410
neither (a) nor (b) washes with
Hayek.

00:05:37.410 --> 00:05:42.879
The reason it doesn't wash is
that he believes in freedom.

00:05:42.879 --> 00:05:47.029
And in free societies,
outcomes are unpredictable.

00:05:47.029 --> 00:05:57.620
We're going to--read this for a
second for yourselves.

00:05:57.620 --> 00:06:01.055
It's the worst sin in the use
of PowerPoint is to put a lot of

00:06:01.055 --> 00:06:03.930
