00:08:31.569 --> 00:08:34.841
Prof: I'd say way less
than one, and I think they would

00:08:34.841 --> 00:08:36.129
say way less than one.
 

00:08:36.129 --> 00:08:42.322
It's because the university has
been invented a piece at a time

00:08:42.322 --> 00:08:44.419
over the centuries.
 

00:08:44.419 --> 00:08:47.470
It's reinvented every day.
 

00:08:47.470 --> 00:08:52.669
What you do in the classroom is
part of reinventing Yale,

00:08:52.669 --> 00:08:56.200
what you do elsewhere is part
of it.

00:08:56.200 --> 00:09:01.533
And the notion of a free
society that Hayek wants to put

00:09:01.533 --> 00:09:06.575
in front of us is one where
agency, the right to make

00:09:06.575 --> 00:09:09.970
decisions, is widely disbursed.
 

00:09:09.970 --> 00:09:15.990
You can imagine societies in
which that isn't true.

00:09:15.990 --> 00:09:17.100
In fact, many exist.
 

00:09:17.100 --> 00:09:21.013
One would be an authoritarian
society, an autocracy,

00:09:21.013 --> 00:09:25.080
where a ruling elite pretty
much says what happens.

00:09:25.080 --> 00:09:30.433
Another would be traditional
society or a theocratic society

00:09:30.433 --> 00:09:36.490
where there are standing rules,
they are more or less followed,

00:09:36.490 --> 00:09:40.418
and they restrict agency in a
sharp way.

00:09:40.418 --> 00:09:48.129
A New Haven colony in the years
1637 to 1665 was a strict

00:09:48.129 --> 00:09:54.000
theocracy,
and the rules were laid down in

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:57.051
the Bible,
solum scripturem [correction:

00:09:57.051 --> 00:09:58.929
sola scriptura]
was the idea.

00:09:58.929 --> 00:10:00.918
They made no laws.
 

00:10:00.918 --> 00:10:04.178
All they did was interpret the
Bible, and enforce it harshly.

00:10:04.178 --> 00:10:10.668
Hayek has in mind something
very different from that,

00:10:10.668 --> 00:10:22.782
and the idea that society is in
some sense a great learning

00:10:22.782 --> 00:10:27.971
machine,
or that a free society is a

00:10:27.971 --> 00:10:34.085
great learning machine,
is the powerful idea in Hayek's

00:10:34.085 --> 00:10:34.750
work.
 

00:10:34.750 --> 00:10:40.384
If we think of--you know,
I'm given to these extravagant

00:10:40.384 --> 00:10:43.081
charts--
historical time on this

00:10:43.081 --> 00:10:46.693
dimension measured,
let's say in centuries,

00:10:46.693 --> 00:10:50.320
or in human generations if you
prefer,

00:10:50.320 --> 00:10:53.783
and on the vertical axis the
total shared store of knowledge

00:10:53.783 --> 00:10:59.187
that that society accumulates,
knowledge as trivial as how to

00:10:59.187 --> 00:11:05.777
manufacture a toothbrush or as
complex as how to operate a

00:11:05.777 --> 00:11:08.090
great university.
 

00:11:08.090 --> 00:11:12.583
The accumulation of that
knowledge is,

00:11:12.583 --> 00:11:18.535
Hayek says, accelerated
exponentially by disbursed

00:11:18.535 --> 00:11:21.330
agency, by freedom.
 

00:11:21.330 --> 00:11:31.394
The rate of accumulation grows
in an exponential curve with a

00:11:31.394 --> 00:11:33.908
free society.
 

00:11:33.908 --> 00:11:38.908
He doesn't talk about
demography, but I would say that

00:11:38.908 --> 00:11:44.567
a free society which has passed
through the world demographic

00:11:44.567 --> 00:11:49.000
transition so that people live
long lives,

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:53.187
lives in which a great deal of
learning can go decade after

00:11:53.187 --> 00:11:55.724
decade,
that such a society,

00:11:55.724 --> 00:12:00.168
embedded in the institutions of
a free society,

00:12:00.168 --> 00:12:06.542
would have the sharpest upward
curve in the accumulation of

00:12:06.542 --> 00:12:08.629
shared knowledge.
 

00:12:08.629 --> 00:12:12.370
The other side of that story,
and here I've added a second

00:12:12.370 --> 00:12:16.014
axis on the right,
which represents the percentage

00:12:16.014 --> 00:12:20.326
of a society's knowledge which
one very competent person can

00:12:20.326 --> 00:12:21.129
capture.
 

00:12:21.129 --> 00:12:24.570
Who's the most competent?
 

00:12:24.570 --> 00:12:26.480
Rick Levin is very competent.
 

00:12:26.480 --> 00:12:31.309
Never brilliant;
always thoroughly competent.

00:12:31.309 --> 00:12:33.039
It's really true.
 

00:12:33.039 --> 00:12:35.678
I mean, it really is true.
 

00:12:35.678 --> 00:12:38.519
I mean, part of why he's so
good is he never tries to be

00:12:38.519 --> 00:12:39.139
brilliant.
 

00:12:39.139 --> 00:12:42.596
He never--have you ever heard
him anything that was even

00:12:42.596 --> 00:12:43.539
vaguely edgy?
 

00:12:43.539 --> 00:12:47.860
I've known him forty years;
we used to ride home together

00:12:47.860 --> 00:12:48.340
at night.
 

00:12:48.340 --> 00:12:54.544
He's never anywhere near the
edge but he's never,

00:12:54.544 --> 00:12:57.259
never, never crazy.
 

00:12:57.259 --> 00:13:01.364
He's just--he's the most
thorough--it's the personality

00:13:01.364 --> 00:13:04.784
profile for an airline pilot,
a heart surgeon,

00:13:04.784 --> 00:13:08.129
and maybe the president of a
university.

00:13:08.129 --> 00:13:15.850
It's a very steady,
very competent persona.

00:13:15.850 --> 00:13:21.850
And Hayek's big point is that
no individual,

00:13:21.850 --> 00:13:25.980
however competent,
can know any major fraction of

00:13:25.980 --> 00:13:28.490
what--
of the knowledge accumulated in

00:13:28.490 --> 00:13:30.019
a free society over time.
 

00:13:30.019 --> 00:13:33.870
And that, first of all that's
humbling.

00:13:33.870 --> 00:13:37.788
It's terrifically humbling.
 

00:13:37.788 --> 00:13:44.134
And part of what the sort of
education all of you are getting

00:13:44.134 --> 00:13:48.470
is about learning what you don't
know,

00:13:48.470 --> 00:13:53.480
and learning where to find out
the things you don't know which

00:13:53.480 --> 00:13:56.110
through time you need to know.
 

00:13:56.110 --> 00:14:02.309
It is not imagined that this or
any other college can create

00:14:02.309 --> 00:14:08.826
graduates who master any large
fraction of what is known in the

00:14:08.826 --> 00:14:13.029
United States or the western
world,

00:14:13.029 --> 00:14:14.950
much less the world at large.
 

00:14:14.950 --> 00:14:20.272
As knowledge accelerates the
individual fraction of that

00:14:20.272 --> 00:14:24.240
knowledge becomes smaller and
smaller,

00:14:24.240 --> 00:14:29.020
and individuals become more and
more dependent on things

00:14:29.020 --> 00:14:31.889
discovered and known by others.
 

00:14:31.889 --> 00:14:35.570
Take the toothbrush.
 

00:14:35.570 --> 00:14:38.529
Who's got a mic here?
 

00:14:38.529 --> 00:14:42.798
