00:19:16.500 --> 00:19:23.190
economy, the knowledge embodied
in it, was enormous.

00:19:23.190 --> 00:19:25.788
It was wholly unoriginal.
 

00:19:25.788 --> 00:19:28.640
Ford was not a brilliant
engineer.

00:19:28.640 --> 00:19:31.318
Some of the people he hired
were damn good engineers.

00:19:31.318 --> 00:19:35.787
By and large though,
they were just regular smart

00:19:35.787 --> 00:19:39.788
people who worked in a
cooperative team way,

00:19:39.788 --> 00:19:43.140
a division of labor about
ideas.

00:19:43.140 --> 00:19:48.095
There was an older idea called
the American system,

00:19:48.095 --> 00:19:53.250
and the American system was
interchangeable parts.

00:19:53.250 --> 00:19:59.259
It was parts made so precisely
identical that you could take

00:19:59.259 --> 00:20:05.166
the left front wheel drum off
one Model T and put it on any

00:20:05.166 --> 00:20:09.140
other Model T and expect it to
fit.

00:20:09.140 --> 00:20:12.712
And that idea--and that's
actually one of the

00:20:12.712 --> 00:20:17.259
revolutionary ideas that's
involved in the vertical spike

00:20:17.259 --> 00:20:21.961
of world affluence,
and which has been disbursed

00:20:21.961 --> 00:20:24.420
everywhere in the globe.
 

00:20:24.420 --> 00:20:27.920
You can't manufacture anything
in a competitive way if you

00:20:27.920 --> 00:20:31.358
don't understand and execute on
interchangeable parts.

00:20:31.358 --> 00:20:37.210
The earliest alleged case was
actually New Haven.

00:20:37.210 --> 00:20:38.838
It was the Eli Whitney gun
factory,

00:20:38.838 --> 00:20:42.366
the waterfall on Whitney
Avenue, the little building

00:20:42.366 --> 00:20:45.627
there,
Eli Whitney had a contract with

00:20:45.627 --> 00:20:49.630
the federal government to make
10,000 muskets.

00:20:49.630 --> 00:20:53.890
He set out to do it with
interchangeable parts,

00:20:53.890 --> 00:20:57.318
and what's fascinating is if
you go out there,

00:20:57.318 --> 00:21:00.528
they've got a couple hundred of
these things in the drawers.

00:21:00.528 --> 00:21:03.900
He got most of them just a
little wrong,

00:21:03.900 --> 00:21:08.394
so he would file them,
or his workers would file them

00:21:08.394 --> 00:21:12.630
and chivy them,
to make them interchangeable.

00:21:12.630 --> 00:21:15.440
But from the point of view of
the military,

00:21:15.440 --> 00:21:16.950
the idea of interchangeability
was huge,

00:21:16.950 --> 00:21:21.440
because when one part of a
weapon jammed,

00:21:21.440 --> 00:21:26.368
you could take another one and
interchange it,

00:21:26.368 --> 00:21:29.976
and the efficiency of the
logistics were enormously

00:21:29.976 --> 00:21:30.769
improved.
 

00:21:30.769 --> 00:21:34.190
The military is not mainly what
that idea is about.

00:21:34.190 --> 00:21:39.160
Anybody have a clue who this is?
 

00:21:39.160 --> 00:21:44.098
Fair enough;
there's no reason you should.

00:21:44.098 --> 00:21:50.490
This is the guy,
Norman Borlaug,

00:21:50.490 --> 00:21:56.346
correct,
who did the critical work on

00:21:56.346 --> 00:22:00.550
developing high growth,
high productivity,

00:22:00.550 --> 00:22:04.295
and disease resistant seeds--
most of the work done fifty or

00:22:04.295 --> 00:22:07.910
sixty years ago,
he died last week--which

00:22:07.910 --> 00:22:12.650
increased agricultural yields on
a world basis.

00:22:12.650 --> 00:22:18.578
There is still hunger in the
world but it's all manmade.

00:22:18.578 --> 00:22:23.039
That is, there are no cases in
the world now where there isn't

00:22:23.039 --> 00:22:25.380
enough food to feed everybody.
 

00:22:25.380 --> 00:22:28.098
There's always enough food.
 

00:22:28.098 --> 00:22:32.180
If it doesn't get to the right
places that's something to do

00:22:32.180 --> 00:22:34.670
with human agency or
institutions.

00:22:34.670 --> 00:22:39.971
And all of us benefit from that
work, and that work in turn

00:22:39.971 --> 00:22:45.089
benefitted from generation after
generation of botany and

00:22:45.089 --> 00:22:46.368
husbandry.
 

00:22:46.368 --> 00:22:52.826
All this process of building
the social store of knowledge is

00:22:52.826 --> 00:22:57.130
what Hayek's idea of freedom is
about.

00:22:57.130 --> 00:23:02.356
This is Dean Mary Miller,
and by now I've beaten this

00:23:02.356 --> 00:23:08.490
horse to death--she's wonderful,
